Unfortunately there are several issues with static and inheritance.

A class based custom configuration is best done **declarative**, in data (properties, XML),
but it can be done in code. The base class can hold a map of all children&#39;s
configuration.

    class Base {

        private static Map&lt;Class&lt;T extends Base&gt;, Config&gt; configByClass = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

        protected Base(Supplier&lt;Config&gt; configProducer) {
            // Could do in constructor:
            configByClass.merge(getClass(), (oldk, k) -&gt; {
                if (oldk == null) {
                    return configProducer.get();
                }
            });
        }

        protected final Config getConfig() {
            // Could do lazy in getter
            configByClass.merge(getClass(), (oldk, k) -&gt; {
                if (oldk == null) {
                    return configProducer.get();
                }
            });
            return configByClass.get(getClass());
        }
    }

    class Child1 extends Base {
        public Child1() {
            super(() -&gt; {
                Config config = new Config(1, 3, 4);
                ...
                return config;
            });
        }

        void f() {
        }
    }

Calling the config supplier _inside_ the constructor has one tiny pitfall: the child class fields are still unavailable, but you did not want to use individual objects anyhow.

